SUDEGO was designed starting from the fact that in the school and in the society there is not enough information on sustainable development. This is an issue of strategic importance for humanity as evidenced by the program launched in late 2015 by the UN focused on 17 goals to achieve for 2030, adopted by the Commission Communication to the European Parliament (22.11.16) and the EU document (Roadmap to a Resource Efficient Europe) that postulates to create a sustainable European economy by the year 2050.
We believe that the world of education is a major player for implementing this process and therefore SUDEGO intends to develop some innovative tools enhancing the basic and higher skills on five of UN goals: 3) health and wellbeing; 5) gender equality; 7) access to clean energy 12) models of sustainable consumption and production; 15) Life on Land.
The proposal was formulated with the objective of complying with the I horizontal priority and the II school priority in the Programme; we involved 7 partners from 5 countries (3 IT, BG, ES, FI, UK), all of them with experience in the field of training and with strong links with the world of school and / or with stakeholders in the productive and social sectors. There are two newcomers to this type of project. There are two local education authorities.
The purpose of the project is to provide, through the work of a transnational team, a consistent set of information and a set of modules for teachers of secondary schools, designed to help them to develop themselves and to suggest for their students a mentality a proactive attitude oriented towards the goal of a sustainable Europe. One of the innovative aspects is the cross-sectoral nature of the project that aimed to recreate, in this case in favor of the school system, a synergy between education and the world of production, also to guide future educational and working choices of the students.
SUDEGO will be organised into 5 IO to create innovative products and 3 activities targeted to a proper and effective management of the project (management, quality, dissemination and sustainability). The final results, which will be offered free of charge on the project website and platform and in the book to all interested users, will be 5:
1) a report on the state of art and the best practices;
2) 5 teaching modules aimed at high school grade I;
3) 5 teaching modules aimed at high school grade II;
4) a raport explaining the results of the testing of the products;
5) a theoretical document intended to contextualize the project, accompanied by the guidelines and the “value giving” characteristics of the products that will be reported in SUDEGO Book.
In the realization of such products we will involve, on the side of partners' experts, teachers of the school system, stakeholders of enterprises and public administration and students of the two degrees.
As for the management of the project, it will be guaranteed by the Coordinator, assisted by the Project Board, to harmonize the commitments and actions to be taken during the process, ensuring proper communication to four targets (project partners, direct and indirect target groups, stakeholders and beneficiaries involved in the activities and the National Agency); 5 project meetings, one in each of the involved countries, will be organized.
The Quality System that will have a system coordinator and a Quality Board will involve all the partners on the basis of a Quality Plan which includes the hazards plan and the conflict resolution procedures. The evaluation will focus on the results and will be organized on the basis of peer review and the general consensus of the partners.
Finally, for the dissemination and sustainability, are expected:
a) a mailing list (for the most part made up of potential users) not limited to the involved countries,
b) the creation of a rich web page appealing and easy to use;
c) the use of blogs and social networks, and connections to the School Education Gateway and eTwinning to trigger a multiplier effect;
d) the organization of the 5 multiplier events, one in each country;
e) the writing up of 4 newsletter;
f) the electronic and paper version of the book contains the papers of O5;
g) the involvement, with the second mailing list, of the local and regional decision makers of school system and all other organizations that deal with sustainable development in all EU countries.
In total at least 1,400 people will be contacted during the life of the project. It will be signed by the partners a sustainability agreement that will commit them to perform a series of actions in the three years after the end of the project, to enable full functionality of the tools developed and a broader dissemination.

Be Wiser examines organisation and technical research challenges in some of Europe’s best known RTD regions. The technology focus is on wireless internet security; while the organisational challenge is to more effectively utilise Triple Helix clusters in regional innovation processes. This approach will strengthen Europe’s position in wireless rollout and address the challenges set out in the Digital Agenda.
With the rapid expansion in wireless based devices, many undertaking complex and often highly confidential transactions, the security of data transmission is increasingly important as trillions of objects are connected via the Internet of Things.
The need for fully secure systems cannot be overstated in retaining the confidence of all users and to balance the requirements of Citizens, Government and Enterprises in terms of their privacy and security needs.
The clusters involved in this project are both central and peripheral and have strong technological complementary skills and experience – they have varying levels of organisational sophistication in terms of how they manage their innovation processes and recognise the potential to mentor each other while working collaboratively on RTD challenges.
Be Wiser will:
• Analyse the regions involved and the sector addressed via triple helix clusters bringing Policy Makers, Researchers and Enterprises together to focus on innovation processes and RTD;
• Develop a JAP and develop smart specialisation strategies and identify further research and product opportunities as part of broader economic development strategies ;
• Deliver tangible outputs that will enhance the competitiveness of the clusters,
• Seek new market opportunities for regional enterprises, especially SMEs;
• Mentor all partner regions on technology, business and clustering themes;
• Develop a sustainable business and resourcing plan.
